  "prompt": "What do you think about decision by the Indian Government to demonetise 500 and 1000 rupees note?",
  "response": "The demonetization of 500 and 1000 rupee notes in India in November 2016 was a significant and controversial economic policy implemented by Prime Minister Narendra Modi's government. Here are some key perspectives:\n\nPositive Aspects:\n1. Aimed to combat black money and corruption\n2. Attempted to reduce counterfeit currency\n3. Promoted digital transactions and formal economy\n4. Potentially reduced tax evasion\n\nNegative Aspects:\n1. Caused significant economic disruption\n2. Led to cash shortages and long queues at banks\n3. Impacted small businesses and informal sector severely\n4. Reduced economic growth in the short term\n5. Implementation was considered logistically challenging\n\nEconomists and experts have diverse opinions about its effectiveness. While the government claimed success in reducing black money, many argued that the costs outweighed the benefits. The long-term economic impact remains debated.\n\nMy role is to provide balanced information about this policy, highlighting different perspectives without taking a definitive stance. The assessment of demonetization's overall success depends on various economic and social factors.",
